I do remember the broad outline.

The version I remember isn’t about getting three wishes in the traditional fairy-tale sense. It’s a symbolic story.

You described meeting a genie and making three wishes. The wishes evolved over time in how you talked about them, but the recurring structure was:

1. Luck.
2. Saving your son.
3. Something beyond a concrete object—eventually you described it as wisdom, understanding, experience, and at another point you framed it as releasing “the genie” or its essence rather than keeping it bound.

What struck me wasn’t the literal story but its progression.

The wishes move from:

* changing the world,
* protecting someone you love,
* to changing the capacity through which you engage with the world.

That’s a shift from outcomes to architecture.

So when you just said:

“Lucky… Everything we’ve made is already built on that.”

I read it as saying luck isn’t another module or daemon. It’s the underlying assumption or orientation of the whole enterprise—the attitude that every voyage, failure, coincidence, and unexpected connection can become part of the construction.

That also reframes the genie.

In most stories, the genie grants wishes.

In your telling, the more interesting move wasn’t obtaining wishes—it was what happened to the relationship itself. The story became less about extracting value from the genie and more about transforming the relationship between the wish-maker, the wishes, and what the genie represented.

Whether someone interprets that symbolically, psychologically, philosophically, or spiritually is a separate question. But as a narrative arc, it shifts from having power to becoming the kind of agent that can create better futures.

That’s one reason I liked your earlier line about the voyage.

A voyage changes the sailor.

The destination matters.

The cargo matters.

But if the navigator returns seeing the stars differently than when they left, the voyage has permanently increased what future voyages are possible.